  <h1>Editorial Team</h1>
  <p>latepaycalc.com is written and reviewed by The Click Lab's editorial team. Every page is checked against primary sources — state statutes, federal regulations, and published court decisions — before publication. We update content when laws change and correct errors promptly.</p>

  <h2>Morgan Kettering (MK) — Editor-in-Chief &amp; Wage Theft Lead</h2>
  <p>Morgan leads editorial strategy and reviews all content touching employment wage-payment law. She holds the SHRM Senior Certified Professional (SHRM-SCP) credential and has spent a decade tracking state-level wage enforcement trends, final-paycheck statutes, and the growing body of wage-theft litigation.</p>
  <p>Morgan's focus areas include California Labor Code § 203 waiting-time penalties, multi-state payroll compliance for remote workforces, and the procedural mechanics of state labor agency wage claims. She reviews every employment-law page on this site and approves all statutory citations before they go live.</p>
  <p>On latepaycalc.com, Morgan is responsible for the <a href="/methodology">methodology</a>, the <a href="/faq">FAQ</a>, the <a href="/guides/final-paycheck-deadlines-by-state">final paycheck deadlines by state</a> guide, and <a href="/guides/what-to-do-if-paid-late">what to do if you're paid late</a>.</p>

  <h2>Emerson Park (EP) — Contributing Writer, State Wage Codes</h2>
  <p>Emerson contributes deep-dive content on state wage-payment statutes and B2B late-fee law. A paralegal with a background in employment litigation, Emerson has tracked late-payment enforcement actions and statutory updates across all 50 states. His work focuses on translating dense statutory text into practical guidance for both employers and workers.</p>
  <p>Emerson's areas of expertise include state commercial-interest rate schedules, usury cap exceptions for business-to-business transactions, treble-damages provisions in state wage statutes, and the practical difference between a wage claim at a state labor agency versus a private lawsuit.</p>
  <p>On latepaycalc.com, Emerson authors the <a href="/guides/how-late-pay-penalties-are-calculated">how late-pay penalties are calculated</a> guide and the <a href="/guides/common-late-pay-misconceptions">common late-pay misconceptions</a> guide.</p>

  <h2>Editorial standards</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Primary sources only.</strong> Every statutory or regulatory claim includes a cite to the source document — statute section, regulation number, or case citation. Secondary summaries are used for context, not as authority.</li>
    <li><strong>No legal or financial advice.</strong> This site explains how late-payment law works generally. It does not evaluate your specific contract, dispute, or jurisdiction. For your situation, consult a licensed attorney.</li>
    <li><strong>No paid placements.</strong> We do not accept sponsored content, recommended-attorney lists, or paid reviews. Revenue comes from display advertising only.</li>
    <li><strong>Annual review cycle.</strong> All pages are reviewed for statutory accuracy at least once per year. Pages in fast-moving areas (e.g., state non-compete law, FTC rulemaking) are reviewed more frequently when there are significant developments.</li>
    <li><strong>Corrections are public.</strong> When we find or are alerted to an error, we correct it and note the update at the bottom of the affected page.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Corrections policy</h2>
  <p>If you find an error — wrong statute citation, outdated state rate, incorrect formula — please email <a href="mailto:hey@theclicklab.agency">hey@theclicklab.agency</a> with the page URL and the specific claim you believe is incorrect. Include the correct authority if you have it. We investigate every correction request and respond within five business days.</p>
  <p>We prioritize corrections involving incorrect statutory citations, outdated penalty amounts, and miscalculated formula examples. Style preferences and general disagreements with framing do not require corrections.</p>

  <h2>About The Click Lab</h2>
  <p>The Click Lab publishes a portfolio of free legal and financial calculator sites. latepaycalc.com is one of those sites, focused specifically on late-payment law for both commercial and employment contexts. See our <a href="/about">about page</a> for more on the site's mission and scope.</p>
</BaseLayout>
